	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				So you think other pet classes are worthy of getting this spell 5 levels after a mages does, huh?  Ok then, don't you think mages are worthy of getting a simple little spell like ROOT maybe 8 levels after EVERYONE else does, which is usually level 4.  Don't you think it's kind of stupid that a level 60 mage must run for his life when his pet dies, all the while getting beat on by some monster, while a level 4 wizard can simply root a mob and run?  And don't tell me &quot;Well, your earth pet roots, that's what pets are for.&quot;  One, the earth pet root is horrible, it lasts maybe 4 seconds IF nothing is hitting the mob.  Two, do you really expect us to use an earth pet ALL the time?  And three, anything over level 45 will absolutely tear through a pet in no time, even the level 57 pet.  <BR>
You say a necromancer has the same issues as a mage.  Well then, mages have the same issues that a necro does.  Except that nobody in Verant seems to care that mages dont get root like necros and every other caster do (not to mention snare), mages have no form of mana regen like every other caster does (mod rods do NOT count), and mages don't get improved invis or invis undead like every other caster does.  But they all get pets.  Even clerics and druids get pets!  You say that the power and diversity of pets is what makes the mage unique.  Then why is it that there is only a 2% increase in power from the 51 earth pet to the 57 pet?  That simply is not enough to keep up with the power increase of the mobs a mage will be fighting at 57.  And why is it that only the 51 and 57 pets can be purchased at a vendor, while every other pet spell must be found?  Tell me where is the diversity in that, when most 54 mages do not have their 54 water pet?  Unless they want to spend 6000 plat for it.  You don't see warriors shelling out 6000 plat for a discipline, a defining characteristic of their class.  And the 52 and 58 Fire pets are a joke.  No mage ever uses these, if they even bother to get them.  Did you know that the 56 necro pet can outdamage every mage pet except perhaps the 59 and 60 pets?<BR>
<BR>
And what about our summoned items?  Nobody wants them.  Everyone can get better stuff than this.  In fact, there are so many items in the game that do this for people anyway.  Need bandages?  Break out the embalmers knife!  And maybe four mages on Karana server have muzzle of mardu.  <BR>
<BR>
Mages are masters of the elements right?  How come no cold damage spells?  Why is it that we are called Elementalist at level 51, but can't even cast a level 8 endure cold on someone else?<BR>
<BR>
I played a magician to level 54, and quit because I could see which way the wind was blowing.  It's no fun playing a class that is so marginalized and ignored.   How long did it take you to realize mage pets weren't dual weilding?  How long did it take you to realize the magician epic was not completable because burning embers and dirt of underfoot were not dropping?  The mage epic is THE hardest and most time consuming quest out of all the classes.  Since getting the mage epic is more about luck than skill, where is the honor and respect in attaining this?<BR>
<BR>
I got out.  I rescued myself from a class that nobody neither wants nor needs.  You can't say I didn't try.  I stuck with it until 54, but I just had to leave before I became too committed.   Maybe it was class envy.  Maybe it just wasn't my calling (I switched to a shaman, and I'm very happy with him).  But to keep ignoring these issues is a tragedy to a class that shows such promise in the beginning but fizzles out near the end.  It was a big let down to me.  Please look into this in your endless quest for class balance.<BR>
<BR>
Mananin Maclyr<BR>
Ex-54 Elementalist <BR>
Karana<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
